\begin{align*}f(x)^2 &= (a-x)^2[(x+\sqrt{x^2+b^2})^2] \\&= [(a-x)x^2+a^2 x^2][x^2+b^2+2x\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}] \\&= x^2[x^2a^2+2a^2b^2-2a(x^2 + b^2)]'][x^2+b^2+2x\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}]+[a(x^2+b^2)-b(x^2a^2+2a^2b^2-2a]^2.\end{align*}Hence, \begin{align*}a^2b^2 &\ge [(a-x)x^2+a^2 x^2][x^2+b^2+2x\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}]= x^4(a^2-1) +2x^3a^2b^2 +x^2b^2(a^2-1) \\&\ge [x^2(a^2 + b^2) +b(2a^2b^2-a)]^2 \Leftrightarrow a^2b^2 \ge x^2[a^2+b^2 +2ab-2ax]^2 \\ &\Leftrightarrow x \ge \frac{a}{a+b} \text{ or } x \le 0.\end{align*}But $x \le 0$ is impossible from the given ineqaution, so we get \textbf{THM 1.} The trinomial $f(x)$ is maximum when $x = \frac{a}{a+b}.$ To maximize $\text{MAX}=2(a-x)(x+\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}),$ first note that $\frac{a}{a+b} \leq a.$ Taking the derivative yields \begin{align*}\frac{d}{dx}(2(a-x)(x+\sqrt{x^2 + b^2})) &= 2(a-x)(\frac{b}{\sqrt{x^2+b^2}}-1)+4a\sqrt{x^2+b^2} \\&= 2a(\frac{(a-x)b}{\sqrt{x^2+b^2}}+2\sqrt{x^2+b^2}-x) \\&= 2a(\frac{(a-x)b}{\sqrt{x^2+b^2}}+1)\sqrt{(x-a)^2+4a^2} \ >= 0,\end{align*}where $4a^2$ is from C-S AM-GM applied to $\sqrt x$ and $\sqrt{x+b}.$ Hence, the trinomial is decreasing, and the maximum is attained when $x=\frac{a}{a+b}.$ Substituting, \begin{align*} \text{MAX} &= 2(a-x)(x+\sqrt{x^2 + b^2}) \\&= 2(a-\frac{a}{a+b})[ \frac{a}{a+b}+\sqrt{(\frac{a}{a+b})^2 +b^2}] \\&= 2(a+\frac{a^2}{a+b})[ \frac{ab}{a+b}.a \\&=\frac{2a^2b(a+b)}{(a+b)^2} + \frac{2a^2b^2}{(a+b)} \\&=2a^2.\end{align*}
</answer>

